<subSubSection lastPageId="75" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="74.[151,1437,1339,2013]" lastBlockId="75.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="75" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1915,1941]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Remarks.</emphasis>
Collection locality notes (R. Rakitov, pers. comm.) recorded the habitat as a dry meadow among pine-yucca forest, with 
<taxonomicName box="[414,506,1951,1977]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[414,506,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Opuntia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and many dry forbs. It would be preferable to describe this species with at least one male specimen, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zahniser" authorityYear="2021" box="[378,531,1987,2012]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecullus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[378,531,1987,2012]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly different and easily separated from the other two species in the genus based on the female. Its discovery substantially expands the known geographic range of the genus. Future collecting efforts directed near the 
<typeStatus box="[424,472,187,213]" pageId="75" pageNumber="76">type</typeStatus>
locality may reveal more specimens including males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
